# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: calculus-of-communicating-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] The **algebra of communicating processes** (ACP) is an algebraic approach to reasoning about concurrent systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] It is a member of the family of mathematical theories of concurrency known as process algebras or process calculi.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] ACP was initially developed by Jan Bergstra and Jan Willem Klop in 1982, as part of an effort to investigate the solutions of unguarded recursive equations.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] More so than the other seminal process calculi (CCS and CSP), the development of ACP focused on the algebra of processes, and sought to create an abstract, generalized axiomatic system for processes, and in fact the term *process algebra* was coined during the research that led to ACP.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] ACP is fundamentally an algebra, in the sense of universal algebra.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] This algebra is a way to describe systems in terms of algebraic process expressions that define compositions of other processes, or of certain primitive elements.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] ACP uses instantaneous, *atomic actions* ( ${\mathit {a,b,c,...}}$ ) as its primitives.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] Some actions have special meaning, such as the action $\delta$ , which represents deadlock or stagnation, and the action $\tau$ , which represents a *silent action* (abstracted actions that have no specific identity).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] Actions can be combined to form *processes* using a variety of operators.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] These operators can be roughly categorized as providing a *basic process algebra*, *concurrency*, and *communication*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] is made does not matter and is left unspecified.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] Note that alternative composition is commutative but sequential composition is not (because time flows forward).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] is no longer observable and has no observable effects.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] ACP fundamentally adopts an axiomatic, algebraic approach to the formal definition of its various operators.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] The axioms presented below comprise the full axiomatic system for ACP $\tau$ (ACP with abstraction).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] When the communications operator is applied to actions alone, rather than processes, it is interpreted as a binary function from actions to actions, $\vert :A\times A\rightarrow A$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] which indicates that a successful interaction $a\vert a$ will be reduced to the action c .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] ACP also includes an encapsulation operator, $\partial _{H}$ for some $H\subseteq A$ , which is used to convert unsuccessful communication attempts (i.e. elements of H that have not been reduced via the communication function) to the deadlock action.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/algebra-of-communicating-processes] Note that the action *a* in the above list may take the value δ (but of course, δ cannot belong to the abstraction set *I*).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] The **calculus of communicating systems** (**CCS**) is a process calculus introduced by Robin Milner around 1980 and the title of a book describing the calculus.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] Its actions model indivisible communications between exactly two participants.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] The formal language includes primitives for describing parallel composition, summation between actions and scope restriction.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] CCS is useful for evaluating the qualitative correctness of properties of a system such as deadlock or livelock.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] According to Milner, "There is nothing canonical about the choice of the basic combinators, even though they were chosen with great attention to economy.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] What characterises our calculus is not the exact choice of combinators, but rather the choice of interpretation and of mathematical framework".
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] The expressions of the language are interpreted as a labelled transition system.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/calculus-of-communicating-systems] Between these models, bisimilarity is used as a semantic equivalence.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A **Petri net**, also known as a **place/transition net** (**PT net**), is one of several mathematical modeling languages for the description of distributed systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] It is a class of discrete event dynamic system.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A Petri net is a directed bipartite graph that has two types of elements: places and transitions.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Place elements are depicted as white circles and transition elements are depicted as rectangles.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A place can contain any number of tokens, depicted as black circles.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A transition is enabled if all places connected to it as inputs contain at least one token.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Like industry standards such as UML activity diagrams, Business Process Model and Notation, and event-driven process chains, Petri nets offer a graphical notation for stepwise processes that include choice, iteration, and concurrent execution.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Unlike these standards, Petri nets have an exact mathematical definition of their execution semantics, with a well-developed mathematical theory for process analysis.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The German computer scientist Carl Adam Petri, after whom such structures are named, analyzed Petri nets extensively in his 1962 Ph.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] An English translation was published in 1966 (Petri 1966).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Despite this, Petri may have invented them in 1939 to describe chemical processes.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A Petri net consists of *places*, *transitions*, and *arcs*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Arcs run from a place to a transition or vice versa, never between places or between transitions.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The places from which an arc runs to a transition are called the *input places* of the transition; the places to which arcs run from a transition are called the *output places* of the transition.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Graphically, places in a Petri net may contain a discrete number of marks called *tokens*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Any distribution of tokens over the places will represent a configuration of the net called a *marking*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In an abstract sense relating to a Petri net diagram, a transition of a Petri net may *fire* if it is *enabled*, i.e. there are sufficient tokens in all of its input places; when the transition fires, it consumes the required input tokens, and creates tokens in its output places.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A firing is atomic, i.e. a single non-interruptible step.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Unless an *execution policy* (e.g. a strict ordering of transitions, describing precedence) is defined, the execution of Petri nets is nondeterministic: when multiple transitions are enabled at the same time, they will fire in any order.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Since firing is nondeterministic, and multiple tokens may be present anywhere in the net (even in the same place), Petri nets are well suited for modeling the concurrent behavior of distributed systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Petri nets are state-transition systems that extend a class of nets called elementary nets.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] 2. $F\subseteq (P\times T)\cup (T\times P)$ is a set of (directed) *arcs* (or flow relations).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] *C* is such that *C* ⊆ *P* is a *configuration*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] *M*: *P* → *Z* is a place multiset, where *Z* is a countable set.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] *M* extends the concept of *configuration* and is commonly described with reference to Petri net diagrams as a *marking*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] *W*: *F* → *Z* is an arc multiset, so that the count (or weight) for each arc is a measure of the arc *multiplicity*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] If a Petri net is equivalent to an elementary net, then *Z* can be the countable set {0,1} and those elements in *P* that map to 1 under *M* form a configuration.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Similarly, if a Petri net is not an elementary net, then the multiset *M* can be interpreted as representing a non-singleton set of configurations.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In this respect, *M* extends the concept of configuration for elementary nets to Petri nets.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In the diagram of a Petri net (see top figure right), places are conventionally depicted with circles, transitions with long narrow rectangles and arcs as one-way arrows that show connections of places to transitions or transitions to places.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] If the diagram were of an elementary net, then those places in a configuration would be conventionally depicted as circles, where each circle encompasses a single dot called a *token*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In the given diagram of a Petri net (see right), the place circles may encompass more than one token to show the number of times a place appears in a configuration.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The configuration of tokens distributed over an entire Petri net diagram is called a *marking*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In the top figure (see right), the place *p*1 is an input place of transition *t*; whereas, the place *p*2 is an output place to the same transition.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Let *PN*0 (top figure) be a Petri net with a marking configured *M*0, and *PN*1 (bottom figure) be a Petri net with a marking configured *M*1.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The configuration of *PN*0 *enables* transition *t* through the property that all input places have sufficient number of tokens (shown in the figures as dots) "equal to or greater" than the multiplicities on their respective arcs to *t*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Once and only once a transition is enabled will the transition fire.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In this example, the *firing* of transition *t* generates a map that has the marking configured *M*1 in the image of *M*0 and results in Petri net *PN*1, seen in the bottom figure.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In the diagram, the firing rule for a transition can be characterised by subtracting a number of tokens from its input places equal to the multiplicity of the respective input arcs and accumulating a new number of tokens at the output places equal to the multiplicity of the respective output arcs.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The following formal definition is loosely based on (Peterson 1981).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In many textbooks, arcs can only have multiplicity 1.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] These texts often define Petri nets using *F* instead of *W*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] When using this convention, a Petri net graph is a bipartite directed graph $(S\cup T,F)$ with node partitions *S* and *T*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The *preset* of a transition *t* is the set of its *input places*: ${}^{\bullet }t=\{s\in S\mid W(s,t)>0\}$ ; its *postset* is the set of its *output places*: $t^{\bullet }=\{s\in S\mid W(t,s)>0\}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Definitions of pre- and postsets of places are analogous.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A *marking* of a Petri net (graph) is a multiset of its places, i.e., a mapping $M:S\to \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] We say the marking assigns to each place a number of *tokens*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] When a transition is enabled in marking *M* and firing it produces a marking $M'$ , we write $M{\underset {G}{\longrightarrow }}M'$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] We are generally interested in what may happen when transitions may continually fire in arbitrary order.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] For a (marked) Petri net $N=(S,T,W,M_{0})$ , we are interested in the firings that can be performed starting with the initial marking $M_{0}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The *reachability graph* of N is the transition relation ${\underset {G}{\longrightarrow }}$ restricted to its reachable markings $R(N)$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A *firing sequence* for a Petri net with graph G and initial marking $M_{0}$ is a sequence of transitions ${\vec {\sigma }}=\langle t_{1}\cdots t_{n}\rangle$ such that $M_{0}{\underset {G,t_{1}}{\longrightarrow }}M_{1}\wedge \cdots \wedge M_{n-1}{\underset {G,t_{n}}{\longrightarrow }}M_{n}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The set of firing sequences is denoted as $L(N)$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A common variation is to disallow arc multiplicities and replace the bag of arcs *W* with a simple set, called the *flow relation*, $F\subseteq (S\times T)\cup (T\times S)$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] This does not limit expressive power as both can represent each other.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Another common variation is to allow *capacities* to be defined on places.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] This is discussed under boundedness below.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The markings of a Petri net $(S,T,W,M_{0})$ can be regarded as vectors of non-negative integers of length $|S|$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] can be used to describe the reachable markings in terms of matrix multiplication, as follows.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] For any sequence of transitions w, write $o(w)$ for the vector that maps every transition to its number of occurrences in w.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] It must be required that w is a firing sequence; allowing arbitrary sequences of transitions will generally produce a larger set.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Meseguer and Montanari considered a kind of symmetric monoidal categories known as **Petri categories**.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Several subclasses of Petri nets have been studied that can still model interesting classes of concurrent systems, while these determinations become easier.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] An overview of such decision problems, with decidability and complexity results for Petri nets and some subclasses, can be found in Esparza and Nielsen (1995).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The reachability problem for Petri nets is to decide, given a Petri net *N* and a marking *M*, whether $M\in R(N)$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] It is a matter of walking the reachability-graph defined above, until either the requested-marking is reached or it can no longer be found.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] This is harder than it may seem at first: the reachability graph is generally infinite, and it isn't easy to determine when it is safe to stop.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In fact, this problem was shown to be EXPSPACE-hard years before it was shown to be decidable at all (Mayr, 1981).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Papers continue to be published on how to do it efficiently.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In 2018, Czerwiński et al. improved the lower bound and showed that the problem is not ELEMENTARY.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In 2021, this problem was shown to be Ackermann-complete (thus not primitive recursive), independently by Jerome Leroux and by Wojciech Czerwiński and Łukasz Orlikowski.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] These results thus close the long-standing complexity gap.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] While reachability seems to be a good tool to find erroneous states, for practical problems the constructed graph usually has far too many states to calculate.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] To alleviate this problem, linear temporal logic is usually used in conjunction with the tableau method to prove that such states cannot be reached.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Linear temporal logic uses the semi-decision technique to find if indeed a state can be reached, by finding a set of necessary conditions for the state to be reached then proving that those conditions cannot be satisfied.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Petri nets can be described as having different degrees of liveness $L_{1}-L_{4}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Note that these are increasingly stringent requirements: $L_{j+1}$ -liveness implies $L_{j}$ -liveness, for ${\textstyle \textstyle {j\in {1,2,3}}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A place in a Petri net is called *k-bound* if it does not contain more than *k* tokens in all reachable markings, including the initial marking; it is said to be *safe* if it is 1-bounded; it is *bounded* if it is *k-bounded* for some *k*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A (marked) Petri net is called *k*-bounded, *safe*, or *bounded* when all of its places are.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A Petri net (graph) is called *(structurally) bounded* if it is bounded for every possible initial marking.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A Petri net is bounded if and only if its reachability graph is finite.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Boundedness is decidable by looking at covering, by constructing the Karp–Miller Tree.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] It can be useful to explicitly impose a bound on places in a given net.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] This can be used to model limited system resources.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Some definitions of Petri nets explicitly allow this as a syntactic feature.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] For example, if in the net *N*, both places are assigned capacity 2, we obtain a Petri net with place capacities, say *N2*; its reachability graph is displayed on the right.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Alternatively, places can be made bounded by extending the net.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] To be exact, a place can be made *k*-bounded by adding a "counter-place" with flow opposite to that of the place, and adding tokens to make the total in both places *k*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] As well as for discrete events, there are Petri nets for continuous and hybrid discrete-continuous processes that are useful in discrete, continuous and hybrid control theory, and related to discrete, continuous and hybrid automata.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] There are many extensions to Petri nets.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Some of them are completely backwards-compatible (e.g. coloured Petri nets) with the original Petri net, some add properties that cannot be modelled in the original Petri net formalism (e.g. timed Petri nets).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Although backwards-compatible models do not extend the computational power of Petri nets, they may have more succinct representations and may be more convenient for modeling.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Extensions that cannot be transformed into Petri nets are sometimes very powerful, but usually lack the full range of mathematical tools available to analyse ordinary Petri nets.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The term high-level Petri net is used for many Petri net formalisms that extend the basic P/T net formalism; this includes coloured Petri nets, hierarchical Petri nets such as Nets within Nets, and all other extensions sketched in this section.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The term is also used specifically for the type of coloured nets supported by CPN Tools.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] There are many more extensions to Petri nets, however, it is important to keep in mind, that as the complexity of the net increases in terms of extended properties, the harder it is to use standard tools to evaluate certain properties of the net.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] For this reason, it is a good idea to use the most simple net type possible for a given modelling task.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Instead of extending the Petri net formalism, we can also look at restricting it, and look at particular types of Petri nets, obtained by restricting the syntax in a particular way.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Ordinary Petri nets are the nets where all arc weights are 1.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] In a marked graph (MG), every place has one incoming arc, and one outgoing arc.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Extended free choice (EFC) – a Petri net that can be *transformed into an FC*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Workflow nets (WF-nets) are a subclass of Petri nets intending to model the workflow of process activities.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The WF-net transitions are assigned to tasks or activities, and places are assigned to the pre/post conditions.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The WF-nets have additional structural and operational requirements, mainly the addition of a single input (source) place with no previous transitions, and output place (sink) with no following transitions.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Accordingly, start and termination markings can be defined that represent the process status.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] WF-nets have the **soundness** property, indicating that a process with a start marking of *k* tokens in its source place, can reach the termination state marking with *k* tokens in its sink place (defined as *k*-sound WF-net).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Additionally, all the transitions in the process could fire (i.e., for each transition there is a reachable state in which the transition is enabled).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A general sound (G-sound) WF-net is defined as being *k*-sound for every *k* > 0.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A directed **path** in the Petri net is defined as the sequence of nodes (places and transitions) linked by the directed arcs.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] An **elementary path** includes every node in the sequence only once.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] A **well-handled** Petri net is a net in which there are no fully distinct elementary paths between a place and a transition (or transition and a place), i.e., if there are two paths between the pair of nodes then these paths share a node.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] An acyclic well-handled WF-net is sound (G-sound).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Extended WF-net is a Petri net that is composed of a WF-net with additional transition t (feedback transition).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The sink place is connected as the input place of transition t and the source place as its output place.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Firing of the transition causes iteration of the process (Note, the extended WF-net is not a WF-net).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] WRI (Well-handled with Regular Iteration) WF-net, is an extended acyclic well-handled WF-net.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] WRI-WF-net can be built as composition of nets, i.e., replacing a transition within a WRI-WF-net with a subnet which is a WRI-WF-net.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] WRI-WF-nets are G-sound, therefore by using only WRI-WF-net building blocks, one can get WF-nets that are G-sound by construction.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The design structure matrix (DSM) can model process relations, and be utilized for process planning.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The **DSM-nets** are realization of DSM-based plans into workflow processes by Petri nets, and are equivalent to WRI-WF-nets.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] The DSM-net construction process ensures the soundness property of the resulting net.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Other ways of modelling concurrent computation have been proposed, including vector addition systems, communicating finite-state machines, Kahn process networks, process algebra, the actor model, and trace theory.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] Different models provide tradeoffs of concepts such as compositionality, modularity, and locality.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/petri-net] An approach to relating some of these models of concurrency is proposed in the chapter by Winskel and Nielsen.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In computer science, the **process calculi** (or **process algebras**) are a diverse family of related approaches for formally modelling concurrent systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Process calculi provide tools for high-level descriptions of interactions, communications, and synchronizations between a collection of independent processes.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] They provide algebraic laws that allow process descriptions to be manipulated and analyzed, and they also permit formal reasoning about equivalences between processes (e.g., using bisimulation).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Leading examples of process calculi include CSP, CCS, ACP, and LOTOS.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] More recent additions to the family include the π-calculus, the ambient calculus, PEPA, the fusion calculus and the join-calculus.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] To define a **process calculus**, one starts with a set of *names* (or *channels*) whose purpose is to provide means of communication.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In many implementations, channels have rich internal structure to improve efficiency, but this is abstracted away in most theoretic models.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In addition to names, one needs a means to form new processes from old ones.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Parallel composition of two processes ${\mathit {P}}$ and ${\mathit {Q}}$ , usually written $P\vert Q$ , is the key primitive distinguishing the process calculi from sequential models of computation.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Parallel composition allows computation in ${\mathit {P}}$ and ${\mathit {Q}}$ to proceed simultaneously and independently.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] But it also allows interaction, that is synchronisation and flow of information from ${\mathit {P}}$ to ${\mathit {Q}}$ (or vice versa) on a channel shared by both.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Crucially, a process may be connected to more than one channel at a time.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Channels may be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In the case of a synchronous channel, the process sending a message waits until another process has received the message.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Asynchronous channels do not require any such synchronization.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In some process calculi (notably the π-calculus) channels themselves can be sent in messages through (other) channels, allowing the topology of process interconnections to change.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Some process calculi also allow channels to be *created* during the execution of a computation.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Interaction can be (but isn't always) a *directed* flow of information.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] That is, input and output can be distinguished as dual interaction primitives.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Process calculi that make such distinctions typically define an input operator (*e.g.* $x(v)$ ) and an output operator (*e.g.* $x\langle y\rangle$ ), both of which name an interaction point (here ${\mathit {x}}$ ) that is used to synchronise with a dual interaction primitive.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Should information be exchanged, it will flow from the outputting to the inputting process.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The output primitive will specify the data to be sent.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In $x\langle y\rangle$ , this data is y .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Similarly, if an input expects to receive data, one or more bound variables will act as place-holders to be substituted by data, when it arrives.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The choice of the kind of data that can be exchanged in an interaction is one of the key features that distinguishes different process calculi.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Sometimes interactions must be temporally ordered.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] For example, it might be desirable to specify algorithms such as: *first receive some data on ${\mathit {x}}$ and then send that data on ${\mathit {y}}$*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] *Sequential composition* can be used for such purposes.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] It is well known from other models of computation.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In process calculi, the sequentialisation operator is usually integrated with input or output, or both.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] For example, the process $x(v)\cdot P$ will wait for an input on ${\mathit {x}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Only when this input has occurred will the process ${\mathit {P}}$ be activated, with the received data through ${\mathit {x}}$ substituted for identifier ${\mathit {v}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The key operational reduction rule, containing the computational essence of process calculi, can be given solely in terms of parallel composition, sequentialization, input, and output.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The details of this reduction vary among the calculi, but the essence remains roughly the same.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Once the message has been sent, $x\langle y\rangle \cdot P$ becomes the process ${\mathit {P}}$ , while $x(v)\cdot Q$ becomes the process $Q[^{y}\!/\!_{v}]$ , which is ${\mathit {Q}}$ with the place-holder ${\mathit {v}}$ substituted by ${\mathit {y}}$ , the data received on ${\mathit {x}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The class of processes that ${\mathit {P}}$ is allowed to range over as the continuation of the output operation substantially influences the properties of the calculus.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Processes do not limit the number of connections that can be made at a given interaction point.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] But interaction points allow interference (i.e. interaction).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] For the synthesis of compact, minimal and compositional systems, the ability to restrict interference is crucial.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] *Hiding* operations allow control of the connections made between interaction points when composing processes in parallel.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Hiding can be denoted in a variety of ways.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] For example, in the π-calculus the hiding of a name ${\mathit {x}}$ in ${\mathit {P}}$ can be expressed as $(\nu \;x)P$ , while in CSP it might be written as $P\setminus \{x\}$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The operations presented so far describe only finite interaction and are consequently insufficient for full computability, which includes non-terminating behaviour.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] *Recursion* and *replication* are operations that allow finite descriptions of infinite behaviour.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Recursion is well known from the sequential world.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Process calculi generally also include a *null process* (variously denoted as ${\mathit {nil}}$ , 0 , ${\mathit {STOP}}$ , $\delta$ , or some other appropriate symbol) which has no interaction points.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] It is utterly inactive and its sole purpose is to act as the inductive anchor on top of which more interesting processes can be generated.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Process algebra has been studied for discrete time and continuous time (real time or dense time).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In the first half of the 20th century, various formalisms were proposed to capture the informal concept of a *computable function*, with μ-recursive functions, Turing machines and the lambda calculus possibly being the best-known examples today.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The surprising fact that they are essentially equivalent, in the sense that they are all encodable into each other, supports the Church-Turing thesis.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Another shared feature is more rarely commented on: they all are most readily understood as models of *sequential* computation.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The subsequent consolidation of computer science required a more subtle formulation of the notion of computation, in particular explicit representations of concurrency and communication.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Models of concurrency such as the process calculi, Petri nets in 1962, and the actor model in 1973 emerged from this line of inquiry.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Research on process calculi began in earnest with Robin Milner's seminal work on the Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) during the period from 1973 to 1980.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Hoare's Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) first appeared in 1978, and was subsequently developed into a full-fledged process calculus during the early 1980s.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] There was much cross-fertilization of ideas between CCS and CSP as they developed.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] In 1982 Jan Bergstra and Jan Willem Klop began work on what came to be known as the Algebra of Communicating Processes (ACP), and introduced the term *process algebra* to describe their work.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] CCS, CSP, and ACP constitute the three major branches of the process calculi family: the majority of the other process calculi can trace their roots to one of these three calculi.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Various process calculi have been studied and not all of them fit the paradigm sketched here.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The most prominent example may be the ambient calculus.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] This is to be expected as process calculi are an active field of study.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Currently research on process calculi focuses on the following problems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The history monoid is the free object that is generically able to represent the histories of individual communicating processes.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] A process calculus is then a formal language imposed on a history monoid in a consistent fashion.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] That is, a history monoid can only record a sequence of events, with synchronization, but does not specify the allowed state transitions.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] Thus, a process calculus is to a history monoid what a formal language is to a free monoid (a formal language is a subset of the set of all possible finite-length strings of an alphabet generated by the Kleene star).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] The use of channels for communication is one of the features distinguishing the process calculi from other models of concurrency, such as Petri nets and the actor model (see Actor model and process calculi).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/process-calculus] One of the fundamental motivations for including channels in the process calculi was to enable certain algebraic techniques, thereby making it easier to reason about processes algebraically.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In logic, a **temporal logic** is any system of rules and symbolism for representing, and reasoning about, propositions qualified in terms of time (for example, "I am *always* hungry", "I will *eventually* be hungry", or "I will be hungry *until* I eat something").
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Temporal logic has found an important application in formal verification, where it is used to state requirements of hardware or software systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] For instance, one may wish to say that *whenever* a request is made, access to a resource is *eventually* granted, but it is *never* granted to two requestors simultaneously.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Such a statement can conveniently be expressed in a temporal logic.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The term *temporal logic* is also sometimes used to refer specifically to **tense logic**, a modal logic-based system of temporal logic introduced by Arthur Prior in the late 1950s, with important contributions by Hans Kamp.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] It has been further developed by computer scientists, notably Amir Pnueli, and logicians.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Though its meaning is constant in time, the statement's truth value can vary in time.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Sometimes it is true, and sometimes false, but never simultaneously true *and* false.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In a temporal logic, a statement can have a truth value that varies in time—in contrast with an atemporal logic, which applies only to statements whose truth values are constant in time.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] This treatment of truth-value over time differentiates temporal logic from computational verb logic.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Temporal logic always has the ability to reason about a timeline.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] So-called "linear-time" logics are restricted to this type of reasoning.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Branching-time logics, however, can reason about multiple timelines.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] This permits in particular treatment of environments that may act unpredictably.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] To continue the example, in a branching-time logic we may state that "there is a possibility that I will stay hungry forever", and that "there is a possibility that eventually I am no longer hungry".
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] If we do not know whether or not I will ever be fed, these statements can both be true.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Although Aristotle's logic is almost entirely concerned with the theory of the categorical syllogism, there are passages in his work that are now seen as anticipations of temporal logic, and may imply an early, partially developed form of first-order temporal modal bivalent logic.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The first system of temporal logic was published in 1947 by Polish logician, Jerzy Łoś.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In his work *Podstawy Analizy Metodologicznej Kanonów Milla* (*The Foundations of a Methodological Analysis of Mill’s Methods*) he presented a formalization of Mill's canons.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In Łoś's approach, emphasis was placed on the time factor.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Thus, to reach his goal, he had to create a logic that could provide means for formalization of temporal functions.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The logic could be seen as a byproduct of Łoś's main aim, albeit it was the first positional logic that, as a framework, was used later for Łoś's inventions in epistemic logic.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The logic itself has syntax very different than Prior's tense logic, which uses modal operators.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The language of Łoś's logic rather uses a realization operator, specific to positional logic, which binds the expression with the specific context in which its truth-value is considered.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In Łoś's work this considered context was only temporal, thus expressions were bound with specific moments or intervals of time.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Arthur Prior was concerned with the philosophical implications of free will and predestination.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] According to his wife, he first considered formalizing temporal logic in 1953.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Results of his research were first presented at the conference in Wellington in 1954.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The system Prior presented, was similar syntactically to Łoś's logic, although not until 1955 did he explicitly refer to Łoś's prior work, in the last section of Appendix 1 in Prior’s *Formal Logic*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Along with **tense logic,** Prior constructed a few systems of positional logic, which inherited their main ideas from Łoś.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Prior gave lectures on the topic at the University of Oxford in 1955–6, and in 1957 published *Time and Modality*, in which he introduced a propositional modal logic with two temporal connectives (modal operators), F and P, corresponding to "sometime in the future" and "sometime in the past".
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In this early work, Prior considered time to be linear.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In 1958 however, he received a letter from Saul Kripke, who pointed out that this assumption is perhaps unwarranted.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In a development that foreshadowed a similar one in computer science, Prior took this under advisement, and developed two theories of branching time, which he called "Ockhamist" and "Peircean".
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Between 1958 and 1965 Prior also corresponded with Charles Leonard Hamblin, and a number of early developments in the field can be traced to this correspondence, for example Hamblin implications.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Prior published his most mature work on the topic, the book *Past, Present, and Future* in 1967.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Work in positional temporal logics was continued by Nicholas Rescher in the 60s and 70s.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In such works as *Note on Chronological Logic* (1966), *On the Logic of Chronological Propositions* (1968)*, Topological Logic* (1968), and *Temporal Logic* (1971) he researched connections between Łoś's and Prior's systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Moreover, he proved that Prior's tense operators could be defined using a realization operator in specific positional logics.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Rescher, in his work, also created more general systems of positional logics.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Although the first ones were constructed for purely temporal uses, he proposed the term **topological logics** for logics that were meant to contain a realization operator but had no specific temporal axioms—like the clock axiom.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The binary temporal operators *Since* and *Until* were introduced by Hans Kamp in his 1968 Ph.D. thesis, which also contains an important result relating temporal logic to first-order logic—a result now known as Kamp's theorem.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Two early contenders in formal verifications were linear temporal logic, a linear-time logic by Amir Pnueli, and computation tree logic (CTL), a branching-time logic by Mordechai Ben-Ari, Zohar Manna and Amir Pnueli.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] An almost equivalent formalism to CTL was suggested around the same time by E.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The fact that the second logic can be decided more efficiently than the first does not reflect on branching- and linear-time logics in general, as has sometimes been argued.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Rather, Emerson and Lei show that any linear-time logic can be extended to a branching-time logic that can be decided with the same complexity.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Łoś’s logic was published as his 1947 master’s thesis *Podstawy Analizy Metodologicznej Kanonów Milla* (*The Foundations of a Methodological Analysis of Mill’s Methods*).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] His philosophical and formal concepts could be seen as continuations of those of the Lviv–Warsaw School of Logic, as his supervisor was Jerzy Słupecki, disciple of Jan Łukasiewicz.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The paper was not translated into English until 1977, although Henryk Hiż presented in 1951 a brief, but informative, review in the *Journal of Symbolic Logic*.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] This review contained core concepts of Łoś’s work and was enough to popularize his results among the logical community.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The main aim of this work was to present Mill's canons in the framework of formal logic.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] To achieve this goal the author researched the importance of temporal functions in the structure of Mill's concept.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Having that, he provided his axiomatic system of logic that would fit as a framework for Mill's canons along with their temporal aspects.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The sentential tense logic introduced in *Time and Modality* has four (non-truth-functional) modal operators (in addition to all usual truth-functional operators in first-order propositional logic).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Kripke models are used to evaluate the truth of sentences in TL.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] A pair (*T*, <) of a set *T* and a binary relation < on *T* (called "precedence") is called a **frame**.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] A **model** is given by triple (*T*, <, *V*) of a frame and a function *V* called a **valuation** that assigns to each pair (*a*, *u*) of an atomic formula and a time value some truth value.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Many sentences are only valid for a limited class of frames.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] It is common to restrict the class of frames to those with a relation < that is transitive, antisymmetric, reflexive, trichotomic, irreflexive, total, dense, or some combination of these.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] **Mirroring**: given a theorem *A*, deduce its **mirror statement** *A*§, which is obtained by replacing G by H (and so F by P) and vice versa.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] **Duality**: given a theorem *A*, deduce its **dual statement** *A**, which is obtained by interchanging ∧ with ∨, G with F, and H with P.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Burgess gives a *Meredith translation* from statements in TL into statements in first-order logic with one free variable *x*0 (representing the present moment).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] where $A^{+}$ is the sentence A with all variable indices incremented by 1 and $a^{*}$ is a one-place predicate defined by $x\mapsto V(a,x)$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Temporal logic has two kinds of operators: logical operators and modal operators.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Logical operators are usual truth-functional operators ( $\neg ,\lor ,\land ,\rightarrow$ ).
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] The modal operators used in linear temporal logic and computation tree logic are defined as follows.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Unary operators are well-formed formulas whenever B(*φ*) is well-formed.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] Binary operators are well-formed formulas whenever B(*φ*) and C(*φ*) are well-formed.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] In some logics, some operators cannot be expressed.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] For example, **N** operator cannot be expressed in temporal logic of actions.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/temporal-logic] A variation, closely related to temporal or chronological or tense logics, are modal logics based upon "topology", "place", or "spatial position".
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] In theoretical computer science, a **transition system** is a state machine that may have infinite states.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] It is used to describe the potential behavior of discrete systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] It consists of states and transitions between states, which may be labeled with labels chosen from a set; the same label may appear on more than one transition.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] If the label set is a singleton, the system is essentially unlabeled, and a simpler definition that omits the labels is possible.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Transition systems coincide mathematically with abstract rewriting systems (as explained further in this article) and directed graphs.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Transition systems can be represented as directed graphs.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Formally, a **transition system** is a pair $(S,T)$ where S is a set of states and T , the *transition relation*, is a subset of $S\times S$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] We say that there is a transition from state p to state q if $(p,q)\in T$ , and denote it $p\rightarrow q$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] A **labelled transition system** is a tuple $(S,\Lambda ,T)$ where S is a set of states, $\Lambda$ is a set of labels, and T , the *labelled transition relation*, is a subset of $S\times \Lambda \times S$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Labels can represent different things depending on the language of interest.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Typical uses of labels include representing input expected, conditions that must be true to trigger the transition, or actions performed during the transition.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Labelled transitions systems were originally introduced as *named* transition systems.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] The formal definition can be rephrased as follows.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Labelled state transition systems on S with labels from $\Lambda$ correspond one-to-one with functions $S\to {\mathcal {P}}(\Lambda \times S)$ , where ${\mathcal {P}}$ is the (covariant) powerset functor.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] In other words, a labelled state transition system is a coalgebra for the functor $P(\Lambda \times {-})$ .
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] There are many relations between these concepts.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Some are simple, such as observing that a labelled transition system where the set of labels consists of only one element is equivalent to an unlabelled transition system.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] However, not all these relations are equally trivial.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] As a mathematical object, an unlabeled transition system is identical with an (unindexed) abstract rewriting system.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] If we consider the rewriting relation as an indexed set of relations, as some authors do, then a labeled transition system is equivalent to an abstract rewriting system with the indices being the labels.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] The focus of the study and the terminology are different, however.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] In a transition system one is interested in interpreting the labels as actions, whereas in an abstract rewriting system the focus is on how objects may be transformed (rewritten) into others.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] In model checking, a transition system is sometimes defined to include an additional labeling function for the states as well, resulting in a notion that encompasses that of Kripke structure.
[src:calculus-of-communicating-systems/transition-system] Action languages are extensions of transition systems, adding a set of *fluents* *F*, a set of values *V*, and a function that maps *F* × *S* to *V*.
